From John Whitmore Subject Re A question about outlet In article Chris Richmond writes In article David Vanderbyl writes In article Russ Crisp writes I'm considering modernizing some old wiring in my home and I need a little advice on outlet Several outlets are the old 'two prong' type without the Naturally the wire feeding these outlets is WITHOUT the ground I noticed at the fusebox that some circuits have the with ground and that on these circuits the ground wire was tied to the same bus as the neutral white This is contrary to the electrical code and should be Well my house was built just last year and the breaker box is wired the same There SHOULD be a connection of the GROUND wire to a ground in the breaker There also should be a connection of the NEUTRAL wire to a ground in the breaker There should be no other place in the building where such a connection occurs not in any of the outlet boxes The NEUTRAL white wire is a 'grounding conductor' for the plug and is NOT safe to touch while the GROUND green wire is a 'protective ground' and carries no current unless some kind of electrical fault has It's safe to touch the protective ground but not to touch the grounding conductor because there is current in the grounding conductor its outlet box end will not be at the same ground potential as its breaker box end John Whitmore